PROJECT: Blog Website with User Authentication and CRUD Operations
============================================================

OVERVIEW
----------------------------------------
This project is a blog website with user authentication and CRUD operations, built using React, Express, and Mongoose. The app allows users to create, read, update, and delete blog posts, and provides a dashboard for managing user data. The app uses a state management service to manage the app's state and provide data to components, and a context management service to provide a context for the app's components to share data. The app is designed to be scalable and maintainable, with a clear separation of concerns between the client-side and server-side code.

COMPONENTS
----------------------------------------
  • server.js  [Server-Side Entry Point]
    Sets up the Express server and routing.

  • auth.js  [Authentication Controller]
    Handles user authentication and authorization.

  • blog.js  [Blog Controller]
    Handles CRUD operations for blog posts.

  • User.js  [User Entity]
    Represents a user entity, including their properties and behaviors.

  • Blog.js  [Blog Entity]
    Represents a blog post entity, including its properties and behaviors.

  • main.jsx  [Client-Side Entry Point]
    Renders the React app.

  • App.jsx  [Main Application Component]
    Renders the app's layout and handles user interactions.

  • myState.jsx  [State Management Service]
    Manages the app's state and provides data to components.

  • myContext.jsx  [Context Management Service]
    Provides a context for the app's components to share data.

ARCHITECTURE PATTERN
----------------------------------------
The app uses a Model-View-Controller (MVC) architecture pattern, with a clear separation of concerns between the client-side and server-side code. The client-side code is responsible for rendering the app's UI and handling user interactions, while the server-side code is responsible for handling business logic and data storage. The app uses a state management service to manage the app's state and provide data to components, and a context management service to provide a context for the app's components to share data. The app's architecture is designed to be scalable and maintainable, with a clear separation of concerns between the different components and services.